This data has been gathered to measure behavioral risk factors for the non-institutionalized adult population (18 years of age and older) residing in the US.

Part 2: Research questions

Research quesion 1:

What is the relationship between the age of onset and affected by Asthma?

#In this question, we are looking for the relationship between the diganosis age of Asthma among population.

#First I want to attach the data

attach(brfss2013)

#Then, we should remove NAs

brfss2013_cleansed1 <- brfss2013%>%
  filter(!is.na(asthmage))
ggplot(brfss2013_cleansed1,
       aes(x = reorder(asthmage, asthmage, function(x)-length(x)))) +
  geom_bar(fill='red') + labs(x='asthmage', y='Frequency')

#Results: As it seems in the plot, most affected people are young ones, especially those who are below the age of 10 (number 97 represents the people who are 10 years old or younger). Therefore, I may conclude that there might be some genetic factors involved in this disease as most people are belonged to their early ages and this hypothesis should be further investigated.

Research quesion 2:

Is there any relationship between the level of income and level of satisfaction among people?

#In this question, I attempted to catagorized people’s income based in level of $K and four classes of satisfaction.

brfss2013<- brfss2013%>%
mutate(income_based_on_K= ifelse(X_incomg=="Less than $15,000","$0-$15K",ifelse(X_incomg=="$15,000 to less than $25,000","$15K-$25K",ifelse(X_incomg=="$25,000 to less than $35,000","$25K-$35K",ifelse(X_incomg=="$35,000 to less than $50,000","$35K-$50K",">$50K")))))
income_level_of_satisfaction <- brfss2013%>%
  filter(!is.na(income_based_on_K), !is.na(lsatisfy))%>%
  group_by(income_based_on_K,lsatisfy)%>%
  summarise(number=n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'income_based_on_K'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(income_level_of_satisfaction,
       aes(x = income_based_on_K, y = number, fill = lsatisfy)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill", stat = "identity")

#Results: As shown, most people who reveive less the $15K, are most dissatisfied while people whose income is more than $50K are placed in the most sattisfied category. We can assume that there is a realtionship between the level of income and level of satisfaction among US citizens.

Now, I am going to figure out the possible relationship between the

menthlthslp <- brfss2013%>%
  filter(sleptim1 %in% c(1:20),!is.na(menthlth))%>%
  group_by(sleptim1)%>%
  summarise(poormnthlth= mean(menthlth))

menthlthslp <- brfss2013%>%
filter(sleptim1 %in% c(1:20),!is.na(physhlth))%>%
group_by(sleptim1)%>%
summarise(poormnthlth= mean(physhlth))

ggplot(menthlthslp, aes(x= sleptim1, y= poormnthlth))+geom_point(color="blue")+geom_line(color="red")+
  ggtitle("The Relationship between Sleep duration and Level of Mental Health") +
  xlab("Sleep") + ylab("Mental Helath")+  geom_smooth(method=lm, level = 0.01, col='black', size=1)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

#Regarding the plot, it can be concluded that there is not any linear relationship between the condition of mental health and the sleep duration among people.
